  ## Usage Details

  The Git command **MUST** be available on the path.

  The git repository should use **Tags** to identify specific version(s).

  Add reference to the package.

  ```XML
  <ItemGroup>
    <GitPackage Include="Sample"
                Version="2"
                Uri="C:\tmp\Sample" />
  </ItemGroup>
  ```
  Where

  |Attribute| Sample|  Description|
  |-------- |--------|-----------|
  | Include | Sample | Name used for package |
  | Version | 2      |Git tag used to identify version |
  | Uri     | C:\tmp\Sample | Uri to git repository |
  
  ### Use a git package without a version
  
  Optionally you can omit the Version attribute.
  
  Without a Version; GitPackage will just use the latest commit it currently has.
  
  Updates then become a manual process.
  
  You can use the MSBuild target : **GitPackRefresh** to fetch the latest for all referenced un-versioned GitPackages.
  
  Or, the simpler approach,
  
  Delete the packages current __.ver__ file; the next build will trigger a fetch and checkout for you.
  ```XML
  <ItemGroup>
    <!--Delete SampleNoVersion.ver to refresh-->
    <GitPackage Include="SampleNoVersion"
                Uri="C:\tmp\Sample"/>
  </ItemGroup>
  ```

